[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926852&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926852&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

In deciding an issue such as whether digits should be allowd as a leading
character in a domain name component, it helps to consider what criteria
might weigh in the decision.

1.  Ease of use by (eventually) hundreds of thousands of users in remembering
corporate domain names for companies like 3COM.COM, 3M.COM, 195Broadway.COM,
etc.

2.  Ability to use IP addresses as opposed to domain names in specifying a
host 

3.  The effort required to change exisiting implementations that check only
the first character of a component.

4.  Because it's the way the standard was written.  Implementors will lose
faith in the standards process if the standard keeps changing.

Given the simple solution outlined by Spencer Love, criteria number 2 is not
relevant.
Criteria 1 argues in favor of changing the standard.  Criteria 3 and 4 argue
for standing pat.  In balancing the alternatives, I believe we should come
down on the side of the users, and the improvement in usability of names if
we adopt the approach of changing the standard.  This won't be the first or
last time a standard has been changed when a way was found to improve
performance or usability.

Marvin Sirbu
CMU

